{"/service/ndnp/iahi/batch_iahi_feebas_ver01/data/sn87058308/00340584144/1913121801/1132.xml":{"full_text":"w\\ wmw?\na\nTHE OSKALOOSA HERALD.\nttblUhed Weekly am Thi*r*d*ys at\nOskaloosa. Mahaska Coiinty, lowa.\nOKALOOSA HERALD COMPANY.\nPublishers.\nCatered at the Postofflce at Oska\nloosa, lowa, as second-class matter.\n\u2022nbecriptlon\u2014Two Dollars Per Tear,\nPayable In Advance.\nOFFICIAL COUNTY PAPER.\n\u00absji^j|^gSP\nLETS BE DOING.\nLet\u2019s put our selfish wants away,\nAnd lay aside our labor.\nTo do some needful act to-day.\nWhich helps our weary neighbor.\nLet\u2019s prove that we're the kind of\nfriend\nMost worth appreciating,\nThe friend indeed, who doesn't spend\nAnother day in waiting.\ni t 1\nLet\u2019s do to-day some kindly deed,\nWhich we have been delaying.\nLet\u2019s give a precious moment\u2019s heed\nAnd do instead of saving.\nLet\u2019s help to make some burden light\nFor one who needs befriending.\nAnd do it now, ere comes the night,\nInstead of just intending.\nLet\u2019s pause today at someone's door,\nWhere long we have been knowing\nThat someone should have paused\nbefore.\nBut they, like we, kept going.\nLet\u2019s strive to soothe the fevered\nbrow.\nThe heart that\u2019s crushed by sorrow,\nAnd let us know \u2019tis needed now,\nBut may not be tomorrow.\nLet's speak today that word of love,\nIf hate we\u2019ve been enthroning.\nA task we've long been thinking of,\nBut just as long postponing.\nMost surely we will find a lot\nOf friendships worth renewing.\nIf we would wake ourselves by not\nJust thinking of, but doing.\nLet\u2019s seek at once the one with whom\nWe\u2019ve long been disagreeing.\nAnd sunshine soon will chase the\ngloom\nWe\u2019ve grown so tired of seeing.\nLet\u2019s greet him with a smile today.\nAnd tell him we regret it.\nAnd likely he\u2019ll be glad to say,\n\u201cMy brother, let\u2019s forget it.\u201d\nLet's try to teach ourselves today,\nThe emptiness of trouble,\nWhich startles us, but floats away,\nAs harmless as a bubble.\nA bugaboo which flies by night\nTo scatter tears and sorrow,\nBut droops before the morning light,\nAnd perishes tomorrow.\nLet\u2019s strive to-day to realize\nThe wrong of evil thinking.\nLet\u2019s look for good with clearer eyes,\nInstead of merely blinking.\nAnd let\u2019s deny each tempting thought\nBefore it lives a minute.\nWhile knowing that the right has\nnaught\nBut what is right within it.\nLet's know that good is always near,\nA thought that\u2019s always pleasant,\nAnd know that evil, doubt and fear.\nCan\u2019t stay where good is present.\nLet\u2019s know God\u2019s love is here at hand\nFor all who will receive it.\nA trutn we may not understand,\nBut true, so let's believe it.\n\u2014Mai Rose\n\u2014Alex Miller declares that \u201cYou do\nnot see a traveling man of any con\nsequence smoking cigarettes.\n\u2014lt is safe to conclude that the\ntalk of W. C. Brown for the governor\nship of lowa did not emanate from\nhim.\n\u2014An Australian wood called yate\nis said to be the strongest known\nand is imported for automobile con\nstruction.\n\u2014lt is predicted that western yel\nlow pine will furnish an excellent\nsource of turpentine as the southern\npine becomes exhausted.\n\u2014The Sioux City Journal laments\n\u201cthat no sooner is one thing done in\nthe way of getting ready for winter\nthan another thing is commenced.\u201d\n\u2014Never treat competition as an\nenemy, like so many of our men in\nbusiness, for so sure as you do it will\nbecome one in reality, a result that\nwill be accomplished principally by\nthe trade. \u2014Frank J. Howell.\n\u2014Another effort is to be made to\nreorganize the league of commericial\nclubs in lowa. This organization\nshould do much good. \u201cBut,\u201d says\nthe Newton Record \"they do not ap\npear to have hit upon the right plan\nfor interesting the people as yet.\u201d\n\u2014Advocates of the capitol park\nplan seem to think that the state re\nquires some evidence of culture.\n\"Well,\u201d comments the Ottumwa Cour\nier, \"you can bank on culture coming\nfast enough after the state has the\nmoney. Make the state wealthy be\nfore paving the streets with gold.\u201d\n\u2014Editor Oallegher, of the Williams\nburg Journal-Tribune, is unable to\nBatisfy his own mind, as to which\ncaused the most damage, the reading\nof the slush printed about the White\nHouse wedding or the barbaric feasts\naround which men stretched 'their\nstomachs in order that they might\nfeel thankful.\n\u2014The Pella Chronicle seems to be\nlooking for something crooked. It\nsays: \"When a college boasts that\nits football team cannot be defeated\non Its home ground, it is time for\ncompeting schools to investigate its\nsystem of operations, not necessar\nily with a view to imitating it, but in\nthe interests of honesty and clean\nsport.\u201d\n\u2014Of all the large and elaborate\n\u25a0M'\nHoliday issues of lowa papers, we\nhave seen none to compare with the\n(wo local papers, the Saturday, Globe,\nand the Oskajopsa Each Is\nput up In magazine form, wltn fine\ncovers and ether exceptionally good\nfeatures. Both are fine specimens\nof the art preservative, and are a\ncredit to the business interests of\nOskalooea.\n\u2014Washington Democrat: \"We are\ninformed that Will Hamilton, dem\nocratic county chairman of Keokuk\ncounty, wil run for congress in the\nSixth district and thus there will be\na hot contest on between him and the\npresent congressman, Sant Kirkpat\nrick. We hope things will not get\nmuddled so as to defeat the demo\ncratic ticket. Bill Hamilton is a\nmighty capable democrat, a good\nspeaker and a good politician and\nwe may look for warm times in the\nold Sixth.\u201d\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nToo much politics and too much\nso-called reforms, are responsible for\nthe business depression now felt in\nthis country, according to Henry\nClews, who in his weekly New York\nreview of trade says:\n\"A careful search of the business\nsituation fails to find any very en\ncouraging features. December is al\nways a month of slowing down, but\nthis year the tendency is more mark\ned than usual. The causes are both\neconomic and political. The most\nfundamental reason is the worldwide\nhigh cost of capital. The signs of re\ncession on this account are quite as\npronounced abroad as in the United\nStates. In Europe the situation is\naggravated by militarism, and in Can\nada by a too rapid expansion. Neith\ner of these conditions exist in the\nUnited States. There has been no\nserious overstrain of credit in this\ncountry; nor any over-expansion in\ngeneral business. On the contrary,\nthe banking situation is pretty well\nin hand, and our various merchandise\nmarkets are more likely to suffer\nfrom scarcity than overproduction.\nAs a matter of fact economic con\nditions in the United States are\nsounder and more encouraging than\nthose prevailing elsewhere. And yet\nbusiness depression is nowhere so\nmarked as along the seaboard of the\nUnited States, and this depression is\ngradually extending itself throughout\nthe West and South. Why should\nthis country suffer a keener reces\nsion in business than any other coun\ntry when intrinsic conditions are\ngenerally sound There is no other\nexplanation for this unfortuate con\ndition of affairs except that of pern\nicious poljiical activity. What with\nthe\" meddling of visionary reformers\nand the attacks of radical politicians\nupon all forms of business activity,\nlegitimate enterprise has been almost\nliterally destroyed. The spirit to ven\nture and invest, which is the main\nspring of industrial progress, has\nbeen thwarted in every direction by\nconstant oppression. Our \u201cnew free\ndom\u201d may be born, but it is not yet\neven a lusty infant, and the country\nis suffering sadly from unwise inter\nference or downright injustice eman\nating from political influences. There\nare signs, however, of a change in\nthis direction; Mr. Wilson, although\na progressive of tremendous power,\n1 seems quite inclined to curb the am\nbitions of extreme radicalism, and\nthere are indications elsewhere that\nour visionary political leaders will be\nforced to sit up and take notice of\nthe consequences of their actions.\nEspecially will this be arue when the\narmy of unemployed increases, as it\nsurely will unless business men are\nspared this incessant irritation and\ninterference with legitimate enter\nprise.\nTHE SPELL OF CHRISTMAS.\nThey are shaping little wonders\nin a million cozy homes,\nDainty fabrics void of blunders.\nDrawn work, bead work, bags fo\nLace creations, ribbon marvels,\nBurnt dreams, paintings half sub\nlime\nGentle fingers all so busy\nFor the coming Christmas time.\nThere are secret conversations\nThat some other must not hear,\nThere are puzzling speculations\nFalling on a friendly ear;\nAnd the air is rife w'lth murmurs\nIn each Christian peopled clime\nLaughter sweetened voices planning\nFor the holy Christmas time.\nFather must not be forgotten\nMother must remembered be\nWith a keepsake wrought or bought\nen\nKin afar and babes on knee\nEach and all heir to a token,\nSomething touched by love that\u2019s\nprime,\nEmblems as from that dear Savior\nWho was born at Christmas time.\nWith our giving, O my brother!\nLet us give a bit of self;\nWithout heart gifts only smother\nHuman longing are but pelf.\nWhile some homely thing and faded\nMay be glorious, sublime,\nIf love's golden kiss is on it\nAt the holy Christmas time.\n\u2014Sioux City Journel.\n\u2014A man with a long head is worth\ntwo with long faces. \u2014Northern Fur\nniture.\n\u2014To get ability out of one\u2019s self\nis to increase one's efficiency, and to\nIncrease one\u2019s value \u2014The Roller\nMonthly.\n\u2014Every politician in the country\nadvises other men to keep out of\npolitics. Maybe, this is one way of\nminimizing competition.\n\u2014\"Those lowa Federal appoints\nments,\u201d says the Sioux Qity Journal,\n\"are expected some time during the\nnext session of congress.\u201d\n\u2014The president hag converted the\nsenate on the thirteen superstition.\nThe senators are to work thirteen\nhours a day on the currency bill.\n\u2014\"If\u201d asks the Anamosa Eureka\n\"the new tariff succeeds in reducing\nMr. Bryan\u2019s living expenses to a point\nbelow his salary, what excuse will he\nhave for talking?\"\nHMjP fTr-!\u00ab M m r H\nThe Annual Pre-Inventory Sale\nNow On At The\n-A (V .w,-J\nN s lu\nOppenheimer Stores\n.I\nMeans Unexcelled Values In Wearables For\nII f 4 j-*' f 4 r, .x,\nMen, Women and Children.\n\u2014ln the opinion of the Vinton\nEagle: The Cedar Rapids Gazette\nis still living back in the woods. Of\nall the good evening dailies in the\nstate it was the only one that didn\u2019t\nissue Thanksgiving.\n\u2014As the,-St. LouiS Globe Democrat\nremarks: Three lawless and despec\nate uegroes can do their race an in\njury that it will take the efforts of\nthousands of honest, peaceful, law\nabiding negroes to repair.\n\u2014The Grinnel! Herald is pleased\nthat Mayor H. G. Lyman has decided\nto be a candidate for county attor\nney. \u2018\u2018His experience as a practicing\nattorney justifies the belief that he\nwill be a successful prosecutor.\"\n\u2014The Ottumwa Courier suggests\nthat a nice Christmas present for\nyourself is a receipt in full for all\ndebts. The man with every debt paid\nis more apt to have a Merry Christ\nmas than the man who forgets that\nhe owes money to someone else.\n\u2014The old familiar strain is thus\ngiven new life by the Delta Press:\nBy the first of the year the publisher\nof this paper has some obligations\nwhich must be met, and we would\nlike to collect in a large amount of\nwhat is due on our subscription list\nbetween now and January 1, 1914.\n\u2014Arthur W. Runft, 17 years old,\nof Grundy county, has won honors\nworth while. Beside making a pro\nit of $133.43 on an acre of lowa corn,\nhe defeated nearly one thousand oth\ner lowa boys for the championship\nof the state acre corn clubs, and wins\nthe free trip to Washington, offered\nby C. B. Hutchinson, of Waterloo.\nAgnes Freidell, of Blackhawl; county,\ngrew 3,403 pounds of tomatoes on a\nlittle less than one-tenth of an acre\nlast season. Her total expense for\nthe ground, work and equipment was\n$23.26, the sale of tomatoes brought\nher $118.14, her net profit totalling\n$92.88. Miss Freidell also wins the\nfree trip to Washington.\nSUNDAY SUBJECTS.\n\u201dA careful search of most church\nes,\u201d says the Continent vPres.) of\nChicago, \u201cwould reveal that there are\nunmustered forces which have never\nbeen called upon. Certainly it is true\nin the church at large. We rejoice\nin the assurance which our leaders\nare giving us that the continual cry\nfor more ministers is being answered,\nand our seminaries are increasing\ntheir enrollment, it would be a pity,\nhowever, if this should keep us from\ncalling out certain forces which we\nhave had all the time. The Presby\nterian church is not half using its\nlaity. We have made almost a fetish\nof the presence of ordained ministers.\nIf there is not a pastor we take it for\ngranted that of course there will be\nno marked growth in the church.\nThere may be two or three elders\nand as many deacons and Sunday\nschool teachers, besides godly women\nnot a few, but we excuse all these\nand explain that the people could not\nhave services since there was no\nminister. As a matter of fact there\nis no reason why our laymen should\nnot go into the pulpit and conduct\nservices, read sermons, or say what\nis in their hearts to say.\u201d\n\u201cOne of the most striking instances\nof the world-wide progress of the Sun\nday school idea is found in the fact\nthat Tokyo, Japan, has invited the\nWorld's Sunday School Convention to\nmeet there in 1916,\u201d says the Sunday\nSchool Times (Bap.) \u2019\"The Japanese\nare keenly interested in the Sunday\nschool as an institution. Their invi\ntation was unanimously accepted at\nZurich.during the World's Convention\nlast July,and this means that the rep\nresentatives of Sunday school work in\nmany lands are gladly recognizing the\ncordiality and earnestness of this in\nvitation, and many are looking for\nward with high expectations to the\nconvention in the Land of the Rising\nSun.\u201d\nProf. H. C. Vedder, of Crozier Theo\nlogical Seminary, says that some peo\nple seem to think that \u201ca preacher\nshould preach, not what he thinks, but\nwhat he thinks other people think he\nought to think.\u201d We think he is\nprobably right; but we think also\nthat in protesting against the slavery\nof other people\u2019s thinking some\npreachers preach not what they think\nbut what they think they think; and\nthey think that thinking people can\nnot tell the difference between really\nthinking and simply thinking that ode\nis thinking! They'd better think\nagain!\nThere are souls in the world who\nhave the gift of -finding joy every\nwhere and leaving it behind them\nwhen they go. Their influence is an\ninevitable gladdening of the heart.\nThey give light without meaning to\nshine. Their bright hearts have a\ngreat work to do for God. \u2014Frederick\nW. Faber.\nPLEA FOR THE RAILROADS.\nCriticism of railroads is no common\nand so popular, that it akes a brave\nman, either in business or politics to\nspeak a good word for them. To be\nsure the big corporations are some\ntimes badly managed, and are so\nmanipulated as to make fortunes for\nthfe few at t)p> expense of the many,\nbut as an industrial factor in the life\nof the nation they must be prosper-\nous else the people will suffer. Dis\ncussing this omnipresent subject,\nHenry Clews in one of his weekly\nNew York letters says:\n\"One of the most Important forms\nthat the current antagonism to big\nbusiness is taking at home, is the re\nfusal of the government, though the\ninterstate Commerce Commission, to\npermit the railroads of this country\nto charge living rates for carrying\nmerchandise. The: Interstate Com\nmerce Commissions; are undoubtedly\ninfluenced, possibly unintentionally\nbiased, by the political and popular\ndisfavor in which the transportation\nlines are concededly held. By adopt\ning this attitude people seem to for\nget entirely tiiat they are injuring\nthemselves. There are probably\nabout 300,000 stockholders in the\nleading railroads of this country.\nThese are direct holders. They con\nstitute a not unsubstantial part of our\nentire population who have their\nsavings thus invested and are en\ntitled as American citizens to the\nfull protection of their property\nrights. But beyond this there are\nvery many millions of our citizens\nwho are indirectly benefited or in\njured by the prosperity or the reverse\nof the railroad lines. 1 refer especial\nly to depositors in banks and policy\nholders in insurance companies. Both\nof these classes >qf. financial institu\ntions have large reserve funds invest\ned in railroad securities. A recent\ncompilation which may serve as an\nilluminating instance shows that the\nsavings bank 3 in six states of the\nEast have 6,036,343 depositors and\nthat 20 per cent of the total deposits\nIn these institutions are invested in\nthe securities of railroads. Every one\nof these 0,636,243 depositors should\nrecognize that he has a personal in\nterest in working in his individual\ncapacity for fair play for the great\ntransportation lines. And it may, I\nbelieve, be tak< for granted that the\nconditions in the six states of which\nstatistics are available are equally\nrepresentative of all the states of the\nUnion. Thus it is hardly possible to\nexaggerate the importance of ade\nquate railroad transportation charges\nto all these interests who are con\ncerned in such a practical manner in\nthe prosperity of the railroads.\nA SYSTEM WORTH STUDYING.\nTlie government of the United\nStates is trying to help the farmer\nborrow money for liis business on\nreasonable terms, at something like\nthe rates other business interests pay.\nTo find the right system it is sending\nexperts to study the schemes useU\nabroad. It seems, however, that we\nhave been overlooking something\nright here at home which may prove\nbetter adapted to the peculiar needs\nof the farmer in this country. A sys\ntem now in successful operation was\nexplained to the Society of Equity\nconvention by George W. Simon of\nChicago, representing the Jewish Ag\nricultural and Industrial Aid Society.\nThis organization we learn from the\nLa Crosse, Wis. Leader-Press, has\nbeen in existence only a few years\u2014\nit was founded in 1900\u2014yet in that\njtime it made 2,600 loans aggregat\ning $1,800,000. It has helped farmers\nin thirty-one states and in Canada,\ncovering a much larger territory than\nall the land credit banks in continent\nal Europe do. Jewish farmers in\nAmerica, whom this society has aid\ned in getting established, now own\nproperty worth $22,000,000, wonder\nful results indeed in a dozen years.\nMr. Simon\u2019s society loans money\nieven on second and third mortgages\nat 4 per cent, an extraordinary low\nrate on loans with country real es\ntate security, which almost invaria\nbly pays at least 6 per cent on gilt\nedge investments and in some states\nruns as high as 12 per cent even on\nfirst mortgages The farmer who\npays 10 or 42 per cent, as those In\nDakotas and further west do, la, of\ncourse, giving the cream of his pro\n\u2018fits to the money lender und would\ngo bankrupt with a volume of busi\nness which to the 4 per cent man\nwould mean prosperity.\nThe system of this Jewish society,\nwhich has produced such wonderful\nresults, is worthy of the study of the\ngovernment experts and the leaders\nof the several societies of farmers.\n\u2014Difficulty is described as oppor\ntunity.\n\u2014Every- means of locomotion seems\nto have its dangers except legs.\n\u2014\u201cFriday, the 13th,\u201d will occur\nthree times in 1924. The jinx still\npursues us.\n\u2014According to \u201clowa Factories\u201d\nthe town is lost when the merchants\npitch horseshoes in tile streets.\n\u2014\u201clf,\u201d says Alex Miller, \"the boss\nthinks he can be late to work and\nmake a winning, he might as well\nmake an assignment right now.\n\u2014To build successfully, one must\nhave pride in the undertaking within\nhis jurisdiction, whether he be a pro\nprietor or a superintendent.\u2014J. Frank\nHowell.\n\u2014The sale of Red Cross seals\nthroughout the country this year\nought to be larger than ever before.\nFor two reasons \u2014first, the message\nthe seal carries is better understood;\nand second the new seal is more at\ntractive.\n\u2014\"Uncle Joe\u201d Cannon says he is\nnot to be compared with President\nWilson as a czar. The ex-speaker\nof the house says the democrats have\nnot made good and that \"in 1916, we\nare going to reverse the engine.\u201d\nUncle Joe is good Republican author\nity.\n\u2014Oskaloosa has been more for\ntunate this year than are many oth\ner cities, because in few cities have\nthere been so many improvemnts in\nproportion to the population. Labor\nhas been more generally employed in\nOskaloosa than in the average muni\ncipality.\n\u2014The S. P. U. G. movement, of\nwhich Mrs. Woodrow Wilson, wife of\nthe president, is the honorary head,\nbears the same relation to Christmas\nthat the Sane Fourth idea does to\nthe observance of Independence day.\nThe society doesn\u2019t call for abolish\nment of tlie gift giving idea, but\ncalls for sane gift giving.\n\u2014The Ottumwa courier observes\nthat in tue face of all the talk about\nthe high price of eggs, lowans kept\nright on eating them, and not at ri\ndiculously high prices either. A cer\ntain state on the Pacific coast which\nhas in the past attracted many peo\nple away from lowa, saw eggs up to\n73 cents a dozen. The lowan who\nstays in lowa gets about the best\nthe country auords.\n\u2014Cot tun consumed during, Octob\ner, 1913, amounted to 542,800 bales.\nCotton on hand in manufacturing es\ntablishments on October 31, was 1,-\n072,274 bales, and in independent\nwarehouses 2.551,964 bales. The num\nber of active consuming cotton\nspindles was 30,833,024. Domestic\ncotton exported during month of No\nvember, 1913, was 1,504,517 running\nbales and foreign cotton imported,\n7,018 equivalent 500-pound bales.\n\u2022\u2014lt is commonly accepted as true\nthat Mount Washington, in New\nHampshire, is the highest mountain\nin the eastern part of the United\nStates. Mount Washington is 6,293\nfeet high, but the Southern Appalach\nians contain many peaks which are\nseveral hundred feet higher than\nNew Hampshire\u2019s famous mountain.\nNorth Carolina has the highest moun\ntain in the Appalachian system,\nnamely. Mount Mitchell, with an\nelevation of 6,711 feet, and Tennes\nsee's highest mountain, Mount Guyot,\nis 6,636 feet above the sea level.\nTHE NEWSPAPER.\nSioux City Journal: It. Is not an\neasy matter to remove the newspaper\nifrom the bargain counter. There is\nnothing on the market go inexpensive\nas a good newspaper. There is noth\ning an intelligent person can buy and\nreceive so much for his money. The\nnewspaper is marked down to such a\npittance that very many people cling\nto the Impression that it is a small\nmatter if they get it for nothing, on\nstraight or crooked lines. The modern\nnewspaper renders great service.\nIt is wonderful how the news of the\nworld is gathered and presented mor\nning and evening. The operation has\nbecome commonplace. And yet only\na few years ago the facilities now em-\nI ployed to bring the ends of the earth\n1 together were unknown. Nothing of\nj large consequence can transpire any\nwhere on the earth or on the sea and\nj escape the observation of the magi\nciuns serving the press. The cost of\n(he service is distributed by means of\na system of co-operation unrivaled ii)\nI other business activities. The first\nj groat contrivance, and great because\nof the wonderful possibilities of which\nit gave the barest hint. Elictricity has\nrevolutionized the newspaper, and to\na surprising extent it lias revolution\nized commerce. There is no dream of\nthe future that may not become real.\nBut the thought is that there'is noth\ning so cheap, considering cost and\nmanifold Retail of service as the mod\nern newspaper. If there was nothing\nbetter than the newspapers of seven\nty five years ago it would be impos\nsible to boast of the greatness of our\ncountry or to be informed in-Tlme to\nenlist interest of what might be hap\npenlng in the next country. The news\npaper, cheap as it ,isi is a great civil\nizer; it is a great agent in the busi\nness of putting people's heads togeth\ner; it is a mighty force fpr the better\nment of nations, and for the bringing\ntogether in amity, all the peoples of\nthe earth. Just think whftt a measly\nsum is involved in the price! Eh? You\nare a reader and paid up? Good for\nHOLIDAY FIRE WARNING.\nOle O. Roe, state fire marshal, has\nj issued the following timely bulletin\nwhich should be studied and heeded:\nITo Merchants:\nInflamSble decoratibns increase the\nfire hatfrird.\nLookout for the wiring of your\nelectric decorations.\nKeep the fire extinguishers in con\ndition for instant us<2.\nWatch the smoker and bis cigar,\nand the \u00fcbiquitous match.\nProtect your lights. A breeze may\nblow a flimsy fabric against an un\nj protected light and start a fire.\nGuard against spontaneous combus\ntion among your piles of holiday\ngoods, l> presiding for reasonable\nj ventilation.\nImpress upon each one of your em\nployes the importance of exercising\nthe utmost cure in guarding against\nj fire.\nClean up your packing rooms and\nbasements daily. Excelsior and\ni Wrapping paper are highly inflam\n'able. Permit no amount of \"busy-\nI ness\u201d to interfere with this precau-\nI tion.\n\u2018\u2018Safety first.\u201d\n!To Parents:\nInflammable Christmas decorations\noftfen cause destructive tires in home\nand church-.\nDon\u2019t hang tissue paper bells or\nother* inflammable decorations in\nclose proximity to a light or fire.\nDon\u2019t use a quantity of highly In\nflammable cotton to represent snow.\nAsbestos fiber, makes fiile snow and\nwill not burn.\nSphta Claus should not wear cot\nton whiskers. Many a life has been\nlost by fire starting in such ardorn\nment.\nDecorations that will burn have\nno place on a Christmas tree. Use\ntinsel or other non-iutlammable ma\nterial.\nChildren should not experiment\nwith matches and candles or other\nthings that produce fire.\nDon't hang celluloid presents on\nthe Christmas tree nor place them\nanywhere near a fire or light. Cel\nluloid is among the most Inflammable\nof substances.\nWatch the tree closely as long as\nthe candles are lighted and have\nmeans, at hand to put out instantly\nany (ire that may start among the\nbranches.\nSet the tree securely so that the\ncan\u2019t tip over. Don\u2019t let the child\nren light the candles.\nInquire as to the safety of the\nplaces of amusement which your\nchildren may attend during the\ncrowded holiday season.\nDon\u2019t let the holiday spirit make\nyou careless in the matter of guard\ning against fire.\nRailroad Business Slumps.\nNorthwestern trainmen at Ames\ndeclare that freight traffic shows a\nmarked decrease over this time a\nyear ago, with no reason for \"slack\nbusiness\u201d advanced. .Ames is an im\nportant junction point of the North-\nWestern lines and is,.-accepted as a\nfair guagp of business in lowa for the\nsystem. It, is reported fi*oip fioone,\na freight point, and location\nof shops, that freight' fralnmen 11113\nenginemen are being laid off.\nAREYOUGOOD FELLOW?\nHelp to Make Every Poor Child\nHappy on Christinas.\nThere are 131 homes in Oskaloosa\ncontaining over 600 children, who are\nlikely to be overlooked by Santa\nClaus, unless the Good Fellows come\nto the rescue and help in a material\nand systematic way. Headquarters\nfor the Good Fellows have been op\nened in the Oskaloosa Commercial\nClub rooms, and some one will be in\ncharge each day from now until\nChristmas, between the hours of 2 to\n5 every afternoon. The telephone\nnumber is 177, and every citizen of\nOskaloosa is invited and urged to\njoin in the work and thereby become\na Good Fellow.\nPeople who care for families regu\nlarly each year are asked to let the\ncommittee know of their wishes and\nintentions at once, that the names\nmay be marked off the lists. Every\none else is urged to come to the club\nroom and select some family or fam\nilies to whom they will play the part\nof Santa Claus.\nIt is the hope and determination of\nthe committee that no child in Os\nkaloosa be overlooked. To this end\nit will require lots of help. Do not\nwait to be asked. Be a volunteer in\nthe good work. Join in at once and\nthus save an undesirable rush at the\nlast moment. By united effort the\ngreat task can easily be handled. Be\na Good Fellow, and do it now.\nANNUAL BAR BANQUET\nMahaska Association Will Dine\nTuesday Evening Dec. 30.\nMahaska County Bar will have its\nannual banquet Tuesday evening, De\ncember 30, which occurs in Holiday\nweek, between Christmas and New\nYear\u2019s.\nSelection of this date was made at\na special meeting called by George\nTrue, president of the Bar Associa\ntion, at the court room. Business af\nfairs received attention and the an\nnual election of officers resulted in\nthe choice of the following:\nPresident, George W. Seevers.\nVice-President, \\V. H. Keating.\nSecretary, Edward A. Schmidt.\nTreasurer, L. T. Shangle.\nExecutive Committee: Officials,\nwith W. R. Lacey, I. C. Johnson and\nH. H. Sheriff.\nAutomobile For Church.\nAn elder of the Latter Day Saints\nchurch in Lainoni has presented his\nchurch with an automobile to be used\nby the officers of the church in mak\ning missionary trips in the near by\ncountry.\nAMERICANS READ\nThe long winter evenings are here\nand you would like to read with com\nfort. Besides ordinary news, there\nwill likely be much of great imiiort\nance in the near future. Congres\nsional news \u2014always interesting\u2014and\nmany men of sound judgment think\nwar with Mexico a foregone conclu\nsion. For comfort to the eyes in\nreading, the newly discovered\n\u201cEye Luminate Lenses\"\nare pre-eminent above all others, not\nonly in ease and comfort in reading,\nbut -also safety and preservation of\neyes and sight.\nThere is real economy in procuring\n\u201cEye Luminate Lenses,\u201d\nas the eye does not grow away from\nthem nearly so soon as with ordinary\nlenses. They filter the light.\nMAYNE ARNOLD OPTICAL CO\u201e\nSole Agents Mahaska County.\nIn office all days but Sunday and\nChristmas.\nNot a Doctor.\n(Advertisement) 1\n.\u00abit& v i\n'\u2022I\nr v;4ff","height":"27732","width":"21756"}}
